===Etymology 1===
Shortened from {{term|hobby-horse}}, from {{etyl|enm|en}} {{term|hoby|lang=enm}}, {{term|hobyn|lang=enm}}, {{term|hobin||small horse, pony|lang=enm}}, from {{etyl|fro|en}} {{term|hobi|lang=fro}}, {{term/t|fro|*haubi}}, {{term|haubby|lang=fro}}, {{term|hobin|lang=fro}} {{gloss|"a nag, hobby"; > Modern French {{term|aubin|lang=fro}}, Italian {{term|ubino|lang=it}}}}, of {{etyl|gem|en}} origin: from {{etyl|fro|en}} {{term|hober|lang=fro}}, {{term|ober||to stir, move|lang=fro}}, from {{etyl|odt|en}} {{term|hobben||to toss, move up and down|lang=odt}}; or from {{etyl|gmq|en}} origin related to {{etyl|da|-}} {{term|hoppe||a mare|lang=da}}, {{etyl|gmq-osw|-}} {{term|hoppa||a young mare|lang=gmq-osw}}, {{etyl|frr|-}} {{term|hoppe||horse|lang=frr}}; both ultimately from {{etyl|gem-pro|en}} {{term/t|gem-pro|*huppōną||to hop}}, from {{etyl|ine-pro|en}} {{term/t|ine-pro|*kewb-||to bend; a bend, joint}}. More at {{l/en|hop}}, {{l/en|hobble}}.

The meaning of ''hobby-horse'' shifted from "small horse, pony" to "child's toy riding horse" to "favorite pastime or avocation" with the connecting notion being "activity that doesn't go anywhere". Possibly originally from a [[proper name]] for a horse, a diminutive of {{term|Robert}} or {{term|Robin}} (compare {{term|dobbin}}).

